Part 4

After Ira, Vikram stopped explaining his evenings to anyone.

Pradhan-babu noticed the office lights stayed on later.

Rohan noticed his brother stopped mentioning names at all, of any kind, the way a man stops walking near a particular pothole after he's twisted his ankle in it once.

Neither said anything.

Work absorbed what the evenings used to hold.

By thirty, the company's Odisha operations ran themselves well enough that Pradhan-babu, now nearing retirement in earnest, told anyone who asked that "Ahuja Sahib could run this with his eyes closed, which is a problem, because a man needs something to keep his eyes open for."

Nobody quite understood what he meant by that except Vikram.

---

The call came on a Tuesday, this time not from an uncle, but from the family doctor directly, in the flat, unhesitating tone doctors use only when there's nothing left to soften.

"Mr. Ahuja, I won't use words like 'let's see.'

Your father's liver has failed past the point where 'let's see' means anything.

Weeks. Possibly a few months, if he's fortunate and careful."

Ten years since the last version of this phone call.

Ten years, and this time the sentence didn't leave any doors open.

Vikram sat with the phone still against his ear long after the doctor had disconnected, the dial tone humming the particular silence of a fact that has stopped being negotiable.

---

Binay insisted on the board meeting anyway.

"If I'm going, Vikram, I'm going having placed you in that chair myself.

Not leaving it for lawyers and vultures to argue over after."

The boardroom held twelve men that morning, the same long table Vikram had once sat beside as a teenager signing things Pradhan-babu told him to sign, except now three of the twelve stood up slightly straighter when he entered, and he'd stopped noticing exactly when that had started happening.

Binay sat at the head, thinner than the frailty of ten quiet years should account for — this was new, sharper, the kind of thin that has a deadline attached to it.

The agenda: South India expansion.

Two new states, three cities, an entirely different tax structure, a market that had ignored the Ahuja name for three generations because the Ahuja name had never once tried to enter it.

Sinha, silver-haired, the one who'd argued for Vikram's seat on this board a decade ago when nobody else had, spoke first.

"We need younger perspective for a market like this. Someone unafraid of an unfamiliar map."

Reddy, older still, arms folded, hadn't looked at Vikram once since the meeting began.

"South India needs experience.

Not a fresh graduate's confidence."

"He's run daily operations here for ten years," Sinha said.

"Here," Reddy said, finally turning to face Vikram directly, not unkindly, simply certain.

"Here, where the ground was already laid by his father, and every supplier already knew the Ahuja name before Vikram walked into a room.

South India will not extend him that courtesy.

Nobody down there has heard of us, and nobody down there owes us patience."

He looked at Vikram properly for the first time.

"What do you know about building something nobody is required to trust yet?"

The room waited.

Vikram thought of a hostel corridor phone, a pathology textbook left unopened on a desk, a factory supervisor twisting his cap saying *sir* to a nineteen-year-old who didn't yet know how to sign his own name properly.

He thought of eleven months fighting a liquor policy nobody else in that room had lost sleep over.

He thought of a stone, and a windshield, and how nobody in this room knew about that either.

Ten years of things nobody in this room had witnessed, and here was Reddy, entirely sincerely, asking what he knew about being unproven.

"Nothing," Vikram said finally. "I know nothing about it yet."

Reddy almost smiled, as if the honesty confirmed something.

"Exactly my point."

"But I know what it costs to become known somewhere new," Vikram continued. "I've paid that particular bill once already. I didn't enjoy it. I'd like the chance to pay it again, somewhere it might actually build something instead of just costing me something."

Nobody in the room understood the second sentence, and Vikram didn't explain it.

Reddy studied him a moment longer.

"Still," he said, not unkindly, "a kid taking on a grown man's risk."

Sinha bristled. "Every leader starts somewhere, Reddy."

"He didn't start today," Reddy said. "That's exactly my worry. He's been quietly competent in a market that forgives him. I don't know yet if he's competent in one that won't."

Binay, from the head of the table, raised one thin hand before the argument could widen.

"Meeting adjourned."

His voice cost him something to produce, audible in the shortness of breath after it.

"We resume tomorrow, once everyone in this room remembers we have less time than we think — some of us considerably less than others."

Chairs scraped back.

Twelve men filed out in the particular silence of people who've been quietly, individually reminded of their own mortality by someone else's.

Vikram remained seated, looking at the empty chairs, at Reddy's unfair-fair question still sitting in the air like smoke that hadn't found a window yet.
